  ('jump-catch-twist-stick-landing', 'Jump-Catch-Twist-Stick Landing layers a clear perception task onto a controlled movement task. The athlete must coordinate eyes, feet, trunk, and hands at the same time, which is the exact problem in sport when a receiver tracks the ball while adjusting to space, pressure, and balance demands.', 'Belongs in Output because the athlete must express fast reaction, acceleration, cutting, jumping, or explosive object control with full attention and low volume. The dominant subrole is Jump, Throw, and Explosive Power.', 'Place early in the session after warm-up, movement prep, and any needed landing preparation. Give enough rest for high-quality intent and clean decisions.', 'Do not use this as a tired finisher. Output reps must stay fast, quiet, organized, and fully recovered; tired reps become conditioning, not coordination quality. Do not progress speed, balance challenge, and decision complexity all at once.', 'Scale one variable at a time: reduce speed first, then reduce decision complexity, object size/speed, stance difficulty, distance, impact, or partner pressure. Progress only when the athlete can explain the cue, catch cleanly, and reset without extra steps.'),
